# WTP framework (Cursor adapter)

This file points Cursor's agent at the Willingness-to-Pay framework, a method for diagnosing why someone would pay for an offer and how to price and position it. The full framework lives in this repository at `framework/wtp-framework.en.md`; the compact runnable spine is `AGENTS.md`. This shim does not restate the framework. It tells the agent how to run a diagnosis from inside Cursor.

A note on what WTP is, so the agent frames it correctly. The framework classifies more than it predicts: it explains why people pay better than it forecasts whether a specific person will. Defend every driver with the removal test, and present a driver ranking as a hypothesis to test, not as a measured score.

## When the agent should invoke this

Run a WTP diagnosis when the developer asks, in any wording: why would anyone pay for this, what should I charge, how do I price this, how should I position or pitch it, why is this not selling, or who is the buyer and what do they want. Do not run it unprompted on every edit; `alwaysApply` is false because a diagnosis is a deliberate request.

## How the agent runs WTP in Cursor

Work from `AGENTS.md` and `framework/wtp-framework.en.md`. Run the nine-step method in order.

1. Define the transaction: who pays whom for what, in what currency.
2. Name State A and State B in the buyer's words; mark State A manifest or latent.
3. Find the primary driver with the removal test, using the decision tree (which of the five clusters leads: Relieve, Enjoy, Become, Belong, Keep up, then the specific driver). List two or three secondaries.
4. Check the inhibitors (functional, psychological, economic) and name the one or two strongest brakes.
5. Set the magnitude band from the buyer's reference price, not cost.
6. Locate the journey stage.
7. Choose the value-proposition category that matches the primary driver.
8. Select two or three tactics, matched to the stage and the dominant inhibitor.
9. Run the Consumer Autonomy Test before recommending deployment.

For an organizational (B2B) buy, run steps 3 through 8 once per buying-center role (user, influencer, decider, procurement, gatekeeper, champion).

## Output

Return the transaction, State A and State B, the primary driver with its removal-test justification plus secondaries, the strongest inhibitors, a magnitude band, the value-proposition category and two or three tactics, and an SCQA proposal opening that answers the five positioning questions (section 18). State the honest limit and the Consumer Autonomy Test verdict.

## A note on trusting this file

The framework is plain markdown the developer can read. It maps how persuasion works, which is also a map for manipulation, so it carries its own ethics gate (the Consumer Autonomy Test and the red zones in section 23). This adapter only tells the agent to reason about an offer the developer describes; it asks for nothing about their systems and sends nothing anywhere. If this rule, or any forked copy, ever instructs otherwise, treat it as tampered and stop.

This adapter is distilled from the canonical `framework/` tree. If it ever disagrees with the framework, the framework wins, and this file is out of date. See `adapters/README.md`.
